A 1 mg/cm2 self-supporting 64Zn (enrich.99.45%)
In this run only light charged particles such
as p, a, and 6He were detected. Hydrogen was
discriminated from He by means of the time of flight
technique using the cyclotron rf as the time reference.
The experimental setup is consisted
of three arrays of highly segmented, large solid
angle Si strip detectors. The detectors used were 20
sectors of the Louvain la Neuve-Edinburgh-detector-
array (LEDA) with a total of 320 strips. The first
array LEDA consisted of eight sectors, placed in an
annular configuration with each sector normal to
the beam direction. The other -LAMP - two arrays each
consisted of six sectors at 45 degr. with respect to
the beam axis.

x4freetext: The experimental setup used in this run was modified
in order to have a more complete angular coverage.
The target was a 0.5 mg/cm2 self-supporting 64Zn
(enrich. 99.45%) foil.
A total of 240 strips were used run hydrogen was
also discriminated from helium using the ToF technique.
The experimental setup was angled at
45 degr. with respect to the beam direction in order
to measure at lab. angles around 90 degr.The detectors
used were two halves of a LAMP detector array, one at
forward and one at backward angles, each consisting of
three sectors. Four double sided silicon strip
detectors covered the angular range from 70. till
100. degr. Two were placed above and two below the
target position.

x4freetext: A stack of four 64Zn (enrich. 99.45%) targets (approx.
2 mg/cm2 thick) followed by 93Nb catchers (approx.
3 mg/cm2 thick) were placed about 70 cm downstream of
the thin 64Zn `scattering` target.
Different activation runs were performed with
6He beams to optimize the production of short lived and
long lived residues. X rays emitted from the different
targets (together with the corresponding catcher) were
measured off-line using Si(Li) detectors surrounded by
lead shields.
Sum of measured heavy products 68Ge, 68Ga, 67Ge, 65Zn.
excitation function obtained by substituting the
experimental 65Zn contribution with the one calculated
by CASCADE.
The largest error in the beam energy occurs at the last
target of the stack and is about +-150 keV.
The error in the calculations was estimated
by using several energy loss programs which gave
a maximum difference of 3%.
